<DESCRIPT>  SAN-FRANCISCO; BRIDGE; AUTO; VEHICLE; COST; INCREASE; CHART  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Directors of the Golden Gate Bridge District on Friday boosted the toll for
cars from $2 to $3, making the new fee three times as expensive as any other
bridge toll in California.;    Directors said without the increase, they would
have to cut transit service by 50 percent and would be unable to retrofit the
54-year-old span to withstand a major earthquake.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MARIN MOANS AT $3 GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE TOLL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to end of article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The new toll takes effect <DATE>July 1.</DATE>;    The action brought hoots from several
residents attending the board meeting. Wearing a broach in the shape of the
Golden Gate Bridge with a tea bag hanging from it, <LOCATION>Tiburon</LOCATION> resident <PERSON>Susan
Deluxe</PERSON> told the board, "This is bad government at its worst.;    " 'I got
ripped off on my way to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>' will become a new saying.";    Carrying
a placard that read, "Fight the <MONEY>$3</MONEY> Toll," <PERSON>Gene Pratt</PERSON> of <LOCATION>San Rafael</LOCATION> told the
board: "We will take this fight to <LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION>. There will be 100,000 of us
before this is over!";    Under the plan adopted by a 13-5 vote, tolls will be
<MONEY>$3</MONEY> for cars, but commuters who use discounted monthly toll books will pay
<MONEY>$2.22</MONEY>, up from <MONEY>$1.67</MONEY>. About <PERCENT>45 percent</PERCENT> of the bridge's motorists use the
advance-purchase discount tickets.;    Fares for Golden Gate Transit buses and
ferries also will increase by <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> each year.;    The increased tolls
and fares are expected to raise <MONEY>$102 million</MONEY>, partly for seismic upgrading on
the bridge. Toll booths will be renovated, and an electronic toll collection
system will be installed.;    The toll increase did not come as a surprise.
The district held four public meetings in <DATE>April</DATE> and <DATE>May</DATE>, and on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the
board's finance committee approved the boost before submitting it to the full
panel.;    The <ORGANIZATION>Bay Area Air Quality Management District</ORGANIZATION> had urged a <MONEY>$3</MONEY> toll to
reduce the number of vehicles on the bridge. One speaker, <ORGANIZATION>Red Dodge</ORGANIZATION>, urged the
toll be raised even higher, to <MONEY>$5</MONEY>, to persuade people to take mass transit.;  
 The board's action <DATE>Friday</DATE> did not alter the current carpool policy. Cars with
three or more occupants do not pay a toll from 5 to <TIME>9 a.m.</TIME> and from 4 to <TIME>6
p.m.</TIME>;    Unlike the state's nine other toll bridges, the Golden Gate Bridge
does not come under the purview of the <ORGANIZATION>State Department of Transportation</ORGANIZATION>. Its
board is independent.;    The current one-way car toll of <MONEY>$2</MONEY> every day has
been in effect since <DATE>1988</DATE>. In <DATE>1981</DATE>, the district voted to make the toll <MONEY>$1</MONEY>
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> through <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, and <MONEY>$2</MONEY> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> and Saturday.;    When the bridge
was opened on <DATE>May 28, 1937</DATE>, the toll was <MONEY>50 cents</MONEY> each way. As the district
paid off its debt, the toll gradually dropped to <MONEY>25 cents</MONEY> each way by <DATE>1955</DATE>. In
<DATE>1968</DATE>, the district began charging tolls only on the way into <LOCATION>San Francisco.</LOCATION>;  
