<HEAD>Quake-Proofing Design Study Set for Golden Gate Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Golden Gate Bridge made it through the
big <DATE>1989</DATE> earthquake without any apparent damage, but bridge
directors think a <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> quake-proofing project would be a
wise investment.
   ``Quite frankly, that's a good bargain,'' said director <PERSON>Jim
Harberson</PERSON>.
   He said replacing the 53-year-old Golden Gate would cost about
<MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY>.
   A committee of bridge directors voted <DATE>Friday</DATE> to spend <MONEY>$550,000</MONEY>
for a design study on a project that would srengthen the bridge so
it can withstand an earthquake with a Richter scale magnitude of 8
or greater.
   The retrofitting project would cost <MONEY>$75 million</MONEY> to <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY>,
and financing remains ``the big question,'' <PERSON>Harberson</PERSON> said.
   The <DATE>October 1989</DATE> earthquake registered 7.1 on the Richter scale
and claimed 67 lives. It knocked out a section of the <LOCATION>San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
