<HEAD>Rush Hour Drive Scratched in Latest Gorbachev Tour Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The threat of rush hour traffic over the
Golden Gate Bridge apparently proved too much for organizers of
<PERSON>Mikhail Gorbachev</PERSON>'s <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> tour.
   Tentative plans were scrapped <DATE>Thursday</DATE> for a <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> motorcade
over the landmark span to <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION>.
   The Soviet leader and his wife, <PERSON>Raisa</PERSON>, will instead view the
bridge from a parking lot on the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> side. <PERSON>Robert
Stockwell</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>Golden Gate Bridge District</ORGANIZATION>, is to give
the Gorbachevs a tour <DATE>Monday</DATE> of gardens near the bridge's toll plaza.
   ``We want to show them the most beautiful part of the bridge and
show them the view that millions of visitors have admired,'' he said.
   Stockwell also is to present the Gorbachevs with several bridge
mementos, including a section of the original suspension cable, a
copy of Chief Engineer <PERSON>Joseph Strauss</PERSON>'s original report on how and
why the bridge was built and a pair of sweat shirts.
   Civic leaders hope the trip will boost <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>'s economic
spirits, devastated by the <DATE>Oct. 17</DATE> earthquake.
   ``<LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> has been feeling some of the downturn in business
ever since the earthquake,'' Chamber of <ORGANIZATION>Commerce</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Carol
Piasente</PERSON> said. ``Having <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> visit is a great boost to the
local economy.''
   At <ORGANIZATION>Stanford</ORGANIZATION>, the post office plans to issue a special envelope
<DATE>Monday</DATE> commemorating the <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> visit with a special cancellation
design featuring <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON>'s face above the word ``Stanford,''
written in Cyrillic alphabet.
   At <ORGANIZATION>City Hall</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, the Soviet flag will be flying.
Mayor Art Agnos, joined by Soviet Consul General <PERSON>Valentin Kamenev</PERSON>
and the city's chief of protocol, <LOCATION>Charlotte</LOCATION> Mailliard Swig, planned
to raise the flag today off the balcony of the mayor's office.
   ``There's a great deal of excitement about the visit,'' said <PERSON>Ms.
Piasente</PERSON> said. ``We're fielding hundreds of phone calls.''
   While <PERSON>Gorbachev</PERSON> meets with <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> business leaders, <PERSON>Mrs.
Gorbachev</PERSON> will take a separate tour of the city <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>,
traveling by motorcade to <LOCATION>Golden Gate Park</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>War Memorial Opera
House</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Davies Symphony Hall</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Bank of America</ORGANIZATION> building and
Fisherman's Wharf.
   Earlier plans to include the Civic Center, where dozens of
homeless people have been living for months, were dropped.
   The Gorbachevs' whirlwind tour _ arriving in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> <DATE>Sunday</DATE>
<TIME>night</TIME> and leaving <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME> _ will include a bit of
socializing.
   Four members of a group called ``Friends of <PERSON>Raisa Gorbachev</PERSON>''
were scheduled to meet with <PERSON>Mrs. Gorbachev</PERSON> at the Soviet consul
general's residence for a ``nonpolitical, people-to-people''
conversation.
</TEXT>
