<DESCRIPT>  BRIDGE; COST; INCREASE; PLANNING; SF-BAY-AREA; ANALYSIS  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A proposal to raise tolls on the Golden Gate Bridge to $3 has roiled this
normally serene enclave and brought a wave of rhetoric more recently heard on
the lips of Soviet dissidents.;    Bridge directors "defy the will of the
people . . . and we have no recourse," complained Gene Prat, one leader of a
group called Marin United Taxpayers Association. "It's undemocratic and
contrary to everything in this country. It's an atrocity."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  $3 'ATROCITY': A TOLL TOO FAR?
GOLDEN GATE PLAN WOULD BE 2ND $1 PRICE HIKE
IN 2 YEARS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related story on P. 2B of this section  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The <MONEY>$1</MONEY> price hike would be the second in <DATE>two years.</DATE>;    The Golden Gate
bridge district says tolls have to be raised to cover a projected <MONEY>$14 million</MONEY>
deficit. The additional money is needed to make the bridge earthquake-safe and
to stanch financial losses from the bus and ferry lines that provide the only
alternative to air-polluting cars, says <PERSON>Carney Campion</PERSON>, the district's general
manager.;    With such seemingly solid reasons for a price hike, one has to
ask: Is a dollar more per day really going to prove a hardship for residents
of the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION>'s wealthiest county?;    <ORGANIZATION>Marin</ORGANIZATION> protesters brush aside such
queries and say that the issue is really one of democratic rights.;    "This
is taxation without representation," Prat said.;    In fact, the <LOCATION>Golden Gate</LOCATION>
bridge district is something of a political anomaly in <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>. It runs the
only toll bridge in the state not operated by <ORGANIZATION>Caltrans</ORGANIZATION>. And its 19-member
board is appointed by six member counties according to a complex formula that
has preserved, even through several changes, its "north-south" balance.;   
That balance means <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> gets nine seats on the board, although
everyone acknowledges that the majority of bridge users are <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION>
residents.;    <ORGANIZATION>Board</ORGANIZATION> members serve at the pleasure of the appointing body --
usually county supervisors or other elected officials -- and many have served
lengthy terms. One, <PERSON>L.E. Castner</PERSON>, a retired insurance executive from <LOCATION>Boyes Hot
Springs</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Sonoma County</LOCATION>, has been on the board since <DATE>1952.</DATE>;    The district's
six counties -- <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Marin</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Sonoma</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Napa</LOCATION>, Mendocino and <ORGANIZATION>Del Norte</ORGANIZATION> --
are the ones that pledged their residents' personal property to guarantee a
bond issue of <MONEY>$35 million</MONEY> to build the bridge, which was completed -- without
a nickel of federal or state money -- in <DATE>1937</DATE>. The bridge was completely paid
off by <DATE>1971</DATE>, which is just around the time the district asked the Legislature
to allow it to begin running bus and ferry lines for commuters.;    One
commuter on board;  Mill Valley Mayor <PERSON>Richard Spotswood</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>
attorney who is the only board member to regularly commute over the bridge,
understands the frustration of fellow <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION> residents.;    "<LOCATION>Marin
County</LOCATION> is not asking anyone to feel sorry for it," said <LOCATION>Spotswood</LOCATION>, who admits
he drives a Mercedes most days rather than taking the bus across the bridge.
"It would just like to control its own destiny.";    But he also notes that a
directly elected board -- a prime goal of the taxpayers group -- would, if
based on population, leave <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION> with even fewer representatives than
the four it now has.;    "It's a quandary," <LOCATION>Spotswood</LOCATION> said.;    About 124,000
cars cross the graceful, 1.7-mile span every day, while a fleet of 270 buses
carries 28,000 commuters and four ferries ply an additional 4,000 across the
bay. Carpools -- about 1,000 a day -- cross free of charge.;    Revenues
shrink;  To a certain extent, the district's success in persuading drivers to
give up their cars for mass transit has hurt its finances, manager <PERSON>Campion</PERSON>
said. A <MONEY>$125 million</MONEY> price tag for earthquake improvements -- even with <PERCENT>80
percent</PERCENT> expected from federal sources -- has only deepened the district's
financial woes.;    It's widely expected that the board will approve the <MONEY>$3</MONEY>
toll later this week, with rate hikes effective <DATE>July 1</DATE>. But the real political
tussle will come over discount rates for commuters -- which now stand at <MONEY>$1.67</MONEY>
but may rise significantly.;    "The average person in <LOCATION>Marin</LOCATION> says <MONEY>$3</MONEY> is a lot
for a toll," <LOCATION>Spotswood</LOCATION> said. "You can give them good reasons but it still just
seems like a lot."  </TEXT>
