<LEADPARA>  An engineering firm has recommended a series of improvements to enable the
Golden Gate Bridge to survive a major earthquake. T.Y. Lin International of
San Francisco recommended strengthening the structure and "tuning" it to make
it less prone to shaking. The project is expected to take five years.
Preliminary cost estimate is $125 million. These are among the key quake
recommendations:; (box)Bridge towers: Strengthen the 746-foot twin steel
spires that form each tower, the struts that connect them, the saddles on top
that hold the main cables and the reinforced concrete piers supporting the
towers. Rebuild connections to roadway supports.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MAKING BRIDGE QUAKE-SAFE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related story on P. 1B of this section  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  (box)Pylons: Strengthen the concrete pylons at each end of the bridge,
anchoring them securely to bedrock, and anchor the steel tie-downs that hold
the bridge's main cables to bedrock.; (box)Viaducts leading to bridge: At both
ends, strengthen the towers and piers that support the roadway trusses, and
the trusses themselves, and install bearings designed to isolate the trusses
from earthquake motion. At the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> end, install shock-absorbing
units in the <LOCATION>Fort Point</LOCATION> arch at far left to dissipate the earthquake's energy.  </TEXT>
