<HEAD>Light Traffic To Welcome Back The Bay Bridge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic flowed smoothly on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the
first workday since the quake-battered Bay Bridge reopened, but
officials said Thanksgiving week could be the cause and suggested
the real crunch could come next week.
   The doctor who cared for Buck Helm, the longshoreman who
survived 3{ days in his car in a collapsed section of Interstate
880, said his death <DATE>Saturday</DATE> was partly due to a heart condition
they had been unaware of.
   However, <PERSON>Dr. Tom McDonald</PERSON>, chief of surgery at <ORGANIZATION>Kaiser Permanente
Medical Center</ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference in <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION> that Helm
suffered ``overwhelming'' injuries in the freeway collapse that
claimed 41 other lives.
   In all, the <DATE>Oct. 17</DATE> quake killed 67 people, injured more than
2,800, left more than 14,000 homeless and inflicted an estimated <MONEY>$7
billion</MONEY> damage.
   The quake sent a 50-foot section of the <LOCATION>San Francisco-Oakland
Bay Bridge</LOCATION>'s upper deck crashing onto the lower deck, cutting the
main link between <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION>. The 8.5-mile-long span
formally reopened <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Traffic <DATE>Monday</DATE> on the bridge was running <PERCENT>50 percent</PERCENT> less than
<DATE>Oct. 17</DATE>, said Lt. <PERSON>Jim Simmons</PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION>Department of
Transportation</ORGANIZATION>, who is toll supervisor at the bridge. Before the
quake, an average of 260,000 cars used the bridge each day.
   ``Obviously, people are still taking mass transit and coming in
earlier,'' said <PERSON>Greg Bayol</PERSON>, a spokesman for the state <ORGANIZATION>Department of
Transportation</ORGANIZATION>. ``The test will come later, this being a holiday
week.''
   Traffic also was down on the Golden Gate Bridge, which handles
traffic southbound into the city. It is used along with the
<ORGANIZATION>Richmond-San Rafael Bridge</ORGANIZATION> by commuters from bedroom communities to
the east.
   From <TIME>6 a.m.</TIME> to <TIME>8 a.m.</TIME>, 14,086 cars used the span, down from
17,634 for the same period a week ago, said Capt. <PERSON>Jackson Fong</PERSON> of
the <ORGANIZATION>Golden Gate Bridge District</ORGANIZATION>. The Golden Gate handles about
146,000 cars daily.
   The Bay Area Rapid Transit system, which set records almost
every day while the Bay Bridge was closed, carried about <PERCENT>20 percent</PERCENT>
fewer passengers during the morning commute than a week ago. By
<TIME>8:30 a.m.</TIME>, the system had transported 65,239 passengers, compared
to 78,003 the previous <DATE>Monday</DATE>, said <ORGANIZATION>BART</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Sy Mouber</PERSON>.
   However, <PERSON>Mouber</PERSON> pointed out that BART carried just 47,415
passengers on <DATE>Oct. 5</DATE>, making <DATE>Monday</DATE>'s load <PERCENT>118 percent</PERCENT> of that
before the quake.
   Asked if these figures meant people have permanently changed the
way they commute, <PERSON>Mouber</PERSON> said, ``I don't think we are seeing the
results yet. I think people are taking an early Thanksgiving
holiday.''
   ``Next week may look a little different,'' said <PERSON>Mike Mills</PERSON>, a
spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>Alameda Contra Costa Counties Transit System</ORGANIZATION>,
which runs public buses.
   The number of passengers taking <ORGANIZATION>AC Transit</ORGANIZATION> buses across the
bridge on routes beginning in <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION> and Alameda appeared to be
down, <PERSON>Mills</PERSON> said.
   The number of people riding a ferry from <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> was also down, according to the <ORGANIZATION>Red &amp; White Fleet</ORGANIZATION>.
Between <TIME>6 a.m. and 9 a.m.</TIME>, there were 1,165 passengers, a drop of
472 from last <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   According to the <ORGANIZATION>Alameda County Coroner's Office</ORGANIZATION>, Helm died of
blunt trauma to his head and body, respiratory failure due to
extensive chest injuries, kidney failure and abdominal infection.
   Before the quake, Helm, 58, had high blood pressure and diabetes.
   Doctors learned after Helm's death that he had an enlarged
ventricle, the chamber of the heart that pumps blood into the
arteries, <ORGANIZATION>McDonald</ORGANIZATION> told reporters. McDonald said it had not been
possible for doctors to know about the heart problem.
   The surgeon said he had been looking forward to taking Helm off
the respirator that kept the longshoreman breathing, and was as
shocked by anyone by his death. ``We had all been so encouraged,''
<ORGANIZATION>McDonald</ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
