<HL> Golden Gate Bridge
Has Troubled Waters
For Its Birthday Bash
---
Squabbling of Rival Groups
Frightens Away Sponsors;
A Job for a Protocol Chief
---
By Carrie Dolan
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 04/29/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> SAN FRANCISCO  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citizen watchdog groups have been formed. 
One man calls it the biggest scandal here in 20 years. 
His opponent deems him "nasty and defaming." 
The mayor has stepped in. 
Sabotage and conspiracy charges are fired. 

   This is serious. 
<LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> is trying to throw a party. 

   The Golden Gate Bridge, one of the world's loveliest ways to cross water, turns 50 next month, and tourist-conscious <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> plans a birthday bash <DATE>May 24</DATE>. 
But as the big day approaches, sponsors are scarce, organizers are about <MONEY>$800,000</MONEY> in debt, and plans have shown all the smooth coordination of Donnybrook Fair. 

   Even for a city that loves a good time, the initial plans for a <MONEY>$22 million</MONEY> extravaganza struck some as a bit overblown. (The 100th-anniversary celebration for the <LOCATION>Brooklyn</LOCATION> Bridge in <DATE>May 1983</DATE> cost about <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY>). 
Some party-poopers even suggested the money might be better spent on the needy. 
San <ORGANIZATION>Francisco Examiner</ORGANIZATION> columnist <PERSON>Bill Mandel</PERSON> wrote, "In money matters, the {bridge} district exhibits the self-control of a 22-year-old rock star with a bad coke habit." 

   Two rival groups vied to be the main merrymakers and planned competing concerts, fireworks and parades. 
Each camp charges the other has torpedoed its fund raising and events. 
The chaos has caused corporate sponsors to back off. 

   Such disarray is surprising in a haven of seasoned socializers. 
In <DATE>May</DATE> alone, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> will have a citywide ball for 12,000 people and the annual Bay to Breakers footrace, the world's largest and wildest, with 100,000 joggers dressed as bowling pins or bananas or pulling kegs of beer. 

   Most <LOCATION>California</LOCATION> bridges are state-run, but the Golden Gate is run by the Golden Gate Bridge, Highway and <ORGANIZATION>Transportation District</ORGANIZATION>, a group of political appointees, and financed by tolls. 
Several members of the group are members of the party committee, known as the Friends of the Golden Gate Bridge. 

   Early on, the bridge bash hit troubled waters. 
The chief fund-raising firm was let go because its task became impossible, an organizer says. 
The events director stepped down. 
A man hired to provide entertainment died shortly afterward. 
At an unveiling of party plans, a map of the Bay area was upside down and an out-of-state organizer told the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> audience, "You <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> people are going to love this!" 

   <PERSON>James Bronkema</PERSON>, the chairman of the Friends, admits, "I could write a book on the mistakes." 
But he blames the local press, too, for making fun of the party. 
He notes that over half the original <MONEY>$22 million</MONEY> budget was for the long-term goal of a museum. 
And he says of rebel reveler <PERSON>Scott Redmond</PERSON>, whose <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> firm produces special events, "Our competitor has been undermining our sponsorship very badly." 

   <PERSON>Mr. Bronkema</PERSON> says <PERSON>Mr. Redmond</PERSON> had a "religious fervor" to have the party. 
"He can have anything he wants, except the bridge. 
After all, that's ours." 

   The bridge directors declined the help of <PERSON>Mr. Redmond</PERSON>, who has staged an outdoor party for 250,000 people, tied the world's largest bow around a hotel, and landed a flying saucer in a corporate board room. 
<PERSON>Mr. Redmond</PERSON> accuses the Friends of sabotage conducted in "the most nasty, heinous way possible" and of seeking political gain. 

   A group called <ORGANIZATION>Citizens for Bridge District Reform</ORGANIZATION> has sent out letters charging that some of the festive doings are part of "<PERSON>David Rockefeller</PERSON>'s overall plan to, figuratively, buy the bridge" and win political favors in order to build a <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. 

   The reference is to <PERSON>James Bronkema</PERSON>'s role as president of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>'s big Embarcadero Center office and shopping complex. 
Embarcadero Center, owned by <PERSON>David Rockefeller</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Prudential Insurance</ORGANIZATION>, donated <MONEY>$250,000</MONEY> to the celebration. 
<PERSON>Mr. Bronkema</PERSON> calls the charges ludicrous and says the donation was "part of our civic duty." 

   Rock promotor <PERSON>Bill Graham</PERSON> volunteered to stage a free show featuring <PERSON>Huey Lewis</PERSON> and the News and the Grateful Dead, two bands with local roots. 
He wanted the bridge closed during the Sunday-afternoon concert to "let her breathe." 
The folks in wealthy <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION>, on the other end of the bridge, protested, so <PERSON>Mr. Graham</PERSON> has canceled. 
But he is frustrated. 
"I feel like I'm tied up with rope, having to watch <PERSON>Ava Gardner</PERSON> parade back and forth in front of me." 

   <PERSON>Joyce Pavlovsky</PERSON>, a member of a citizens' group called Bridgewatch, says <PERSON>Marinites</PERSON> fear medical emergencies if the bridge is closed, not to mention the inconvenience. 
"It's going to be such a mess," she says. 
"This is not an occasion for fun." 

   <PERSON>Herb Caen</PERSON>, the columnist for the <LOCATION>San Francisco Chronicle</LOCATION>, riled some by asking why "the spoiled brats in Marin" couldn't stand being out of their BMWs for a few hours. 
<PERSON>Mr. Caen</PERSON>, one of 200,000 who walked across the bridge the day it opened, also wrote that rock music has little to do with the bridge. 
<PERSON>Mr. Graham</PERSON> responded to <PERSON>Mr. Caen</PERSON>'s opinion by calling him "an amoeba filled with pus." 

   With plans going badly awry, organizers belatedly brought in <LOCATION>Charlotte</LOCATION> "Tex" <ORGANIZATION>Mailliard</ORGANIZATION>, a wealthy widow renowned as a party thrower and the city's acting chief of protocol. 
<PERSON>Mrs. Mailliard</PERSON>, who served Cheerios to 10,000 people at a farewell breakfast for the queen of <LOCATION>England</LOCATION>, threw a citywide celebration for the cable cars, shot off fireworks inside city hall and enlisted the <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>'s aid in baking the world's largest birthday cake to mark <ORGANIZATION>Beethoven</ORGANIZATION>'s birthday, is known to stay and sweep up after her affairs. 

   "I never would have forgiven myself if there wasn't a celebration for the bridge," <PERSON>Mrs. Mailliard</PERSON> says. 
The bridge can be viewed from many places in her home, including the shower. 

   <PERSON>Mrs. Mailliard</PERSON> enlisted the aid of Mayor <PERSON>Dianne Feinstein</PERSON>. 
The city donated <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY>, and the mayor has been successfully urging corporations to make "modest" contributions. 
Although the party has been "one controversy after another," Mayor <PERSON>Feinstein</PERSON> concedes, "controversy is an everyday part of life here." 

   Plans of the <ORGANIZATION>Friends</ORGANIZATION> committee now include a dawn walk across the bridge, <PERSON>Tony Bennett</PERSON> singing again about his misplaced heart, fireworks, new lighting for the bridge and a performance by a marching band from <LOCATION>Pottstown</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pa.</LOCATION>, the city that made the steel for the bridge. 
The current budget is about <MONEY>$3 million</MONEY>, including in-kind contributions. 
The group <PERSON>Mr. Redmond</PERSON> works with plans art shows, whaleboat races and a stamp-cancellation festival. 

   The celebration will clearly out-glitz last <DATE>November</DATE>'s festivities for the 50th anniversary of the Bay Bridge, connecting <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION>. 
The Bay Bridge, always in the shadow of its sister span, celebrated with a string of lights, a 250-foot candle and a donated fireworks show, all costing about <MONEY>$225,000</MONEY>. 
"We wanted a low-cost, dignified celebration," a spokesman says. 
Bay Bridge officials had asked Golden Gate directors if they could celebrate together, the spokesman says, but the Golden Gaters replied, "We're professionals -- have your own party." 

   The Bay Bridge is overshadowed in other ways by the <LOCATION>Golden Gate</LOCATION>. 
A few years ago a study showed that distraught people drive across the Bay Bridge in order to jump off the Golden Gate, one of the world's leading suicide sites. 

   About 20 miles from <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, the people in <LOCATION>Crockett</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, population 3,000, will be throwing a shindig for the highly untouted <LOCATION>Carquinez</LOCATION> bridge, which turns 60 the week before the <ORGANIZATION>Golden Gate</ORGANIZATION>'s 50th. 

   The <PERSON>Crockett</PERSON> blowout will feature the release of a couple of thousand pigeons, and its own bridge lighting and rock concert. 
<PERSON>Gene Pedrotti</PERSON>, a local hardware-store owner, arranged for the donation of 500 flashlights and for residents to stand under their bridge and click them on at the same time. 
"We're not a controversial party," he allows. 

</TEXT>
