<LEADPARA>  Golden Gate Bridge officials said Thursday they are considering fines of up to
$10,000 for people arrested while blocking the span.;    The move comes in
response to a protest Tuesday against war in the Middle East in which hundreds
of demonstrators paralyzed commuter traffic.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PROPOSED FINE FOR GOLDEN GATE PROTEST: $10,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "We are trying to devise some penalty other than a slap on the wrist for
disruption," said <ORGANIZATION>Golden Gate Bridge District</ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON>Gary Giacomini.</PERSON>;   
"The bridge is a vital artery for many people no matter how noble the cause of
the demonstration.";    Currently, a maximum fine of <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY> can be imposed on
bridge trespassers.;    Changes in the law under which penalties are levied
require authorization by the state Legislature.;    The full board will see
the proposed changes <DATE>Jan. 25</DATE>.  </TEXT>
