<HEAD>Minor Earthquakes Shake Northern California</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with USGS reducing Richter reading
to 3.0 sted 3.6; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``We had ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake early today shook a
wide area of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, the sixth tremor in <LOCATION>Northern California</LOCATION>
within 24 hours, officials said.
   No damage or injuries were immediately reported from the quakes,
whose magnitudes ranged from 2.4 to 3.0 on the Richter scale.
   The sixth quake struck at <TIME>12:01 a.m.</TIME> and had a magnitude of 3.0
on the Richter scale, according to the <ORGANIZATION>United States Geological
Survey</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>National Earthquake Information Center</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Golden</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colo</LOCATION>.
   It was centered west of the Golden Gate Bridge, the same area as
two earlier ones, said seisomologist <PERSON>Anthony Lomax</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>University
of California Seismology Station</ORGANIZATION>.
   ``We had several calls from all over the city but so far no
reports of damage,'' said a <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> police dispatcher who
declined to give his name.
   The first quake, which measured 2.7 on the Richter scale, struck
at <TIME>11:49 a.m.</TIME> <DATE>Sunday</DATE> and was centered about five miles west of the
bridge.
   Within two minutes, two more quakes, measuring 2.6 and 2.4 on the
Richter scale, were felt in southern <LOCATION>Marin County</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Lomax</PERSON> said.
   At <TIME>10 p.m.</TIME>, a magnitude 3.0 quake struck the same general area
off the Golden Gate as the first one, <PERSON>Lomax</PERSON> said.
   A quake that measured 2.9 was centered near <LOCATION>San Leandro</LOCATION>, about 10
miles south of <LOCATION>Berkeley</LOCATION>, at <TIME>10:41 p.m.</TIME>, he said.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   A quake of magnitude 3.5 can cause slight damage.
   The <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> earthquake of <DATE>1906</DATE> measured an estimated 8.3 on
the Richter scale.
</TEXT>
