<HEAD>Companies Offer To Help Quake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-SF Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the midst of disaster, some companies
have stepped forward to offer free services to those in need, from
legal advice to fresh pasta.
   Lawyer <PERSON>Melvin Belli</PERSON> and his staff set up tables <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>
<TIME>afternoon</TIME> in front of his downtown offices, offering free legal
counsel to the public, said <PERSON>Marian Ashley</PERSON>, an employee at <ORGANIZATION>Belli</ORGANIZATION>'s
<LOCATION>Sacramento</LOCATION> office.
   <PERSON>Ashley</PERSON> said <PERSON>Belli</PERSON> and his attorneys were not working out of
their office because the building was apparently unsafe.
   <ORGANIZATION>Bechtel Group Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, one of the world's biggest engineering
companies, loaned the city of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> the services of its
civil and structural engineers, said spokesman <PERSON>Larry Miller</PERSON>.
   ``This is our hometown and we'd like to help in whatever way we
can, and we thought this was the best way,'' said <PERSON>Miller</PERSON>. He said
similar assistance was also offered to <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION> and the state.
   <PERSON>Miller</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Bechtel</ORGANIZATION> started trying to contact its estimated 200
engineers in the <LOCATION>Bay</LOCATION> area beginning <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>. As of <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>,
25 to 30 were helping the city inspect buildings.
   He said more engineers would be offered to the municipalities as
they report in to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> headquarters. The <ORGANIZATION>Bechtel</ORGANIZATION> office
was otherwise closed <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   ``We have got a total of 1,500 projects going on in the world
... so the expertise here is pretty deep,'' said <PERSON>Miller</PERSON>. ``It's a
valuable commodity to have, and we are just happy to loan it to the
city.''
   Cellular One of <LOCATION>Burlingame</LOCATION> offered to lend free cellular phones
to any emergency service agencies that need them, according to
spokeswoman <PERSON>Carolyn Casey</PERSON>.
   The company, which also has an office in <LOCATION>Oakland</LOCATION>, has asked
individual customers to refrain from using the network to give
better access to relief workers.
   She said the company has more than 400 channels, with a capacity
to handle about 200,000 cellular phones.
   ``We've had over 500 phones go out our door, to emergency
agencies all over the <LOCATION>Bay</LOCATION> area,'' said <PERSON>Casey</PERSON>. ``We're doing
everything we can. We have people manning our system 24 hours a
day.''
   The Golden Gate Bridge on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> did not charge a toll for
commuters from <TIME>6 a.m.</TIME> to noon, in an effort ``to help alleviate the
flow of traffic, the traffic crunch that never happened,'' said
<PERSON>Bruce Selby</PERSON>, spokesman for the Golden Gate Bridge and <ORGANIZATION>Highway
Transportation District</ORGANIZATION>.
   The district anticipates much more traffic today because of the
closed Bay Bridge.
   People left hungry got some help from the Aunti Pasta retail
store chain. Every person who entered one of the eight Aunti Pasta
stores in the <LOCATION>East Bay</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> was offered one-third
pound of fresh pasta.
   ``We really want to help people out,'' said <PERSON>Julie Kramer</PERSON>,
manager of one store where at least 30 people in two hours had come
in to get pasta.
   ``I think we all want to help out in whatever way we can,'' said
<PERSON>Kramer</PERSON>. ``It's our little effort.''
</TEXT>
