<DESCRIPT>  STANFORD; STUDENT; SUICIDE; BRIDGE; SAN-FRANCISCO; MARIN; COUNTY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Stanford University announced Monday that a 24-year-old man who died after
apparently jumping off the Golden Gate Bridge on Thursday was one of its
students.;    Richard Woodland Tanner, a senior majoring in international
relations, was scheduled to graduate in June, according to a university
official.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GOLDEN GATE BRIDGE JUMPER IDENTIFIED AS STANFORD
STUDENT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     A spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION>California Highway Patrol</ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>'s parked car
was found <DATE>Thursday</DATE> on the Golden Gate Bridge. The <ORGANIZATION>CHP</ORGANIZATION> said an eyewitness saw
him get out of the car, go the guardrail and jump at about <TIME>10:30 p.m.</TIME>;    <ORGANIZATION>The
Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> conducted a search that night but did not find the body, Chief
Warrant Officer <PERSON>Lance Jones</PERSON> said. No further searches are planned.;    <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>
lived in <LOCATION>Escondido Village</LOCATION> with his wife, <PERSON>Chantal</PERSON>, according to a spokeswoman
for the university. He was an active member of the <ORGANIZATION>Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints</ORGANIZATION> and had served a two-year mission for the church.;    He is
also survived by his parents, <PERSON>Dr. William</PERSON> and <PERSON>Elizabeth Tanner</PERSON>, and three
older brothers, <PERSON>W. Brent</PERSON>, Troy, and <PERSON>Steven</PERSON>, all of <LOCATION>Los Angeles.</LOCATION>;    Memorial
services are to be held on campus during the first week in <DATE>April</DATE>, said <PERSON>Jean
Kim</PERSON>, assistant dean of residential affairs.  </TEXT>
