<HEAD>Landmarks in Good Shape, Tourists Not Welcome Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT category code; LEADS with 3 grafs
to fix typo in `San Francisco,' some cable car service back; picks up 3rd
pvs: `Automobiles were...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC PREWITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cable cars returned to the streets of <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, after being stuck in their barn since an
earthquake knocked out electrical power two days earlier.
   By midday, enough traffic signals were working again so that
partial service on the popular tourist attraction could resume.
   Most of the city's landmarks, including the Golden Gate Bridge,
Coit Tower, Mission <PERSON>Dolores</PERSON> and the colorful Victorian-style homes,
were virtually unaffected by the powerful quake and remained
unruffled and picturesque as ever.
   Automobiles were snaking down the ``Crookedest Street in the
World'' of postcard fame, the block of Lombard on Russian Hill.
   ``The traffic hasn't stopped at all, except <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> when
they closed the street off because a cable car was stuck at the top
of the hill,'' said <PERSON>Jason Doty</PERSON>, who lives on the steep, winding
street. ``Our electricity is still out, but there are no other
problems here.''
   Not all the frequently photographed landmarks got through the
earthquake untouched, of course.
   The <LOCATION>San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge</LOCATION>, big sister of the more
colorful Golden Gate, was crippled. Some <MONEY>$4,000</MONEY> worth of glass was
broken at the <ORGANIZATION>Conservatory of Flowers</ORGANIZATION>, a huge greenhouse in <LOCATION>Golden
Gate Park</LOCATION>. At the bayside end of Market Street, the flag atop the
Ferry Building was tilted and the tower clock was still stuck on
<DATE>Tuesday</DATE>'s late-afternoon earthquake time, <TIME>5:04 p.m.</TIME>
   The Mansion Hotel, a Victorian building in the <LOCATION>Pacific Heights</LOCATION>
district, rode smoothly through its second major quake.
   ``It stood proud, and it's obviously a survivor. It looks
fragile but it isn't,'' owner <PERSON>Bob Pritikin</PERSON> said of the building
completed in <DATE>1887</DATE>. ``The only damage we found was a crack in a
bathroom ceiling.''
   Alcatraz, called ``The Rock'' by those who did chilly hard time
there when it was a federal prison, certainly lived up to its
nickname. Tourists _ though very few of them _ in the Fisherman's
Wharf area <DATE>Thursday</DATE> were pointing their cameras at the bleak island
in the bay.
   ``We like <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Alex Camenisch</PERSON> of Marthalen,
<LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION>, said as he and his family strolled through Fisherman's
<LOCATION>Wharf</LOCATION>, where there was no power and almost all businesses were
closed.
   They were not planning on staying overnight, however. ``We were
going to stay at a downtown hotel, but now we're going to stay
somewhere else,'' said <PERSON>Camenisch</PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON>Esther</PERSON>.
   On <LOCATION>Nob Hill</LOCATION>, about half the <ORGANIZATION>Fairmont Hotel</ORGANIZATION>'s 500 rooms were
empty as well as dark <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>. A national business group
that had reserved 450 rooms canceled a scheduled meeting.
   ``I was on the phone starting <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>morning</TIME> to groups with
reservations here the next 30 days. News reports have made things
sound pretty dismal, and I wanted to let them know the city was not
burning down,'' said <PERSON>Stan Boyd</PERSON>, director of sales for the Fairmont.
   At the <ORGANIZATION>Moscone Center</ORGANIZATION>, the city's largest convention center, one
event ended its run <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>. The next, a car dealers' gathering set
for <DATE>Oct. 26</DATE>, is still scheduled, as well as a convention of 5,000
plastic surgeons beginning <DATE>Oct. 27</DATE>.
</TEXT>
