<HEAD>Meandering Whale Swims Under Golden Gate and Out to Sea</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Humphrey swimming under the
Golden Gate and out to sea. Pick up 6th graf pvs, `Humphrey, a...'
Denize cq in 8th graf; Gibeson cq in 14th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC PREWITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Humphrey the wayward whale swam under the
Golden Gate Bridge <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and headed toward the open sea, ending
a four-day visit that saw one wrong turn after another.
   The 45-ton humpback whale passed under the span about <TIME>5 p.m.</TIME>,
escorted by a flotilla of small boats, <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> vessels and
private cruisers.
   People on the bridge cheered as <PERSON>Humphrey</PERSON> swam by.
   He headed back to the ocean where he belongs a day after he was
freed from a stranding on mud flats along the shore of <LOCATION>San
Francisco Bay</LOCATION>.
   For a time, the mammoth mammal seemed to be re-enacting his <DATE>1985</DATE>
tour of <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> bay. Then, the wayward whale was tracked by
legions of well-wishers as he meandered, far from the open ocean
where he belongs, for 25 days.
   Anxious rescuers tracked the whale through the day as he seemed
to be headed anywhere but out to sea. First he was seen south of
the bridge, then away to the north.
   Rescuers mobilized to intercept the 45-ton whale and try to
induce him to head out to sea, she said. After the 40-foot <PERSON>Humphrey</PERSON>
was freed from the mud flat <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> evening he seemed to have
gotten his bearings, raising hopes he would join the rest of his
kind, which feed in the bay sometimes, but seldom stay for long.
   ``He was swimming well and going toward the Golden Gate,''
<PERSON>Denize Springer</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>California Marine Mammal Center</ORGANIZATION> said early
in the day. ``Well, he wasn't really going in just one direction.
Whales tend to meander.''
   Humphrey, for some reason attracted to <LOCATION>San Francisco Bay</LOCATION>, has a
history of meandering.
   In <DATE>1985</DATE>, when the news media gave him his name, he went through
the bay and up the <LOCATION>Sacramento River</LOCATION>, with much of the nation
tracking his wanderings.
   On <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <PERSON>Humphrey</PERSON> veered off course again, turning left into
<LOCATION>San Francisco Bay</LOCATION> as his fellow migrating whales continued south
along the <LOCATION>West Coast</LOCATION>.
   He spnnt about 24 hours stuck on the mud flat before the <ORGANIZATION>Coast
Guard</ORGANIZATION>, the incoming tide and a crowd of cheering spectators helped
shake him loose <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>.
   Experts could only speculate about why <PERSON>Humphrey</PERSON> went off course.
   ``Your guess is as good as mine. But my guess is something's
wrong with this guy,'' said <PERSON>Brian Gibeson</PERSON>, a marine biologist at
the <ORGANIZATION>California Academy of Sciences</ORGANIZATION>.
   It could be that a parasite has affected his brain or
rudimentary inner ear, <PERSON>Gibeson</PERSON> said, making <PERSON>Humphrey</PERSON> ``like a car
with his wheels out of alignment.''
</TEXT>
