<HEAD>Yacht Beats 135-year New York-San Francisco Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 10th graf, `Dozens..', with trip completed
in 80 days and 20 hours and other records broken. Picks up 11th graf, `In
a...'. SUBS 14th graf, `The crew...', to give hometowns.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1, FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yacht <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child sailed
triumphantly under the Golden Gate Bridge on <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, breaking by
eight days the New York-to-San Francisco speed record set in <DATE>1854</DATE>.
   The 60-foot sloop crossed the finish line at <TIME>12:32 p.m.</TIME> and was
met by cheers and yells from hundreds of spectators. <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s
Child set sail <DATE>Nov. 23</DATE> on a 14,500-mile voyage that took it around
treacherous <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION> on the tip of <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>.
   ``I wouldn't do anything different, but I wouldn't do it again _
once is enough,'' said skipper-owner <PERSON>Warren Luhrs</PERSON> after he stepped
ashore.
   Luhrs and the other two crew members waved to the crowd after
bettering the 89-day, eight-hour trip by the 229-foot clipper ship
Flying Cloud during the Gold Rush.
   The crew docked the 10-ton vessel at <ORGANIZATION>Blossom Rock</ORGANIZATION>, about two
miles from the <LOCATION>Golden Gate</LOCATION>, because they said the submerged point is
where clipper ships used to drop anchor.
   About 80 ships were out on <LOCATION>San Francisco Bay</LOCATION> to greet the modern
racing sloop, while other spectators gathered on the roof of <LOCATION>Fort
Point</LOCATION> and at the south tower of the Golden Gate Bridge. A biplane
flew overhead trailing a sign that read: ``We love you TC.''
   <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child's entrance into the bay was delayed for hours by
a four-knot outgoing tide and by a lack of wind.
   The crew tried everything, including putting out a large sail
called a spinnaker, but all its sails drooped. Finally, under a
bright, cloudless sky the yacht was able to sail under the Golden
Gate.
   Dozens of sailboats and powerboats had headed out the Golden Gate
for the occasion and the <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> sent a 95-foot cutter and four
utility boats to escort the yacht into the bay and lessen the danger
of a spectator boat accidentally ramming <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child.
   The yacht left from <LOCATION>Sandy Hook Bay</LOCATION>, 18 miles south of <LOCATION>New York
City</LOCATION>, and arrived in <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> after 80 days and 20 hours, said
<PERSON>Thomas Conroy</PERSON>, race timekeeper at the <ORGANIZATION>St. Francis Yacht Club</ORGANIZATION>. He
said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child broke three other sailing records; <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to
the equator, set in <DATE>1856</DATE>; <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION>, <DATE>1857</DATE>; and <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION>
to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>, <DATE>1854</DATE>. The times and old records were not
immediately available.
   In a ship-to-shore interview earlier <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, crew member <PERSON>Courtney
Hazleton</PERSON> said he had ``that coming-home feeling.''
   ``It's kind of like a mixed bag of emotions right now,'' said
<PERSON>Hazleton</PERSON>. ``Both relief, letdown, that the whole thing's over, and
just a general feeling of accomplishment.''
   The crew _ <PERSON>Hazleton</PERSON>, 32, of <LOCATION>Palmetto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>; <PERSON>Luhrs</PERSON>, 44, of
<LOCATION>Alachua</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>; and <PERSON>Lars Bergstrom</PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION>Sarasota</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla</LOCATION>, who helped
design the vessel _ had spent <DATE>Saturday</DATE> zig-zagging north against a
stubborn headwind that delayed the ship's arrival by one day.
   Luhrs launched <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child for the <DATE>1984</DATE> solo trans-Atlantic
race, in which she was the first American entry and the first
single-hulled boat to finish.
   The Flying Cloud was a merchantman that also ferried Gold Rush
adventurers around the dangerous <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION> at the tip of <LOCATION>South
America</LOCATION> and up to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>. It could carry 35 sails on its tall
masts and was the fastest of thousands of clippers that raced each
other across the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>.
   The ship wrecked on rocks off <LOCATION>St. Johns</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Newfoundland</LOCATION>, in <DATE>1874</DATE>
and nothing is left of it.
   In the past seven years, five racing boats trying to beat Flying
Cloud's record sank in the howling gales and treacherous rocks of
<LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION>.
   A second boat also attempting to break Flying Cloud's record was
damaged last week in a storm off <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION>. The Bark of the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>, a
60-foot monohull, was in its 56th day of sailing.
   <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s Child also had trouble during its run at the record;
it had to stop at the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> for repairs after it struck
an unknown object.
   The modern vessel survived <LOCATION>Cape Horn</LOCATION>, but <LOCATION>Hazleton</LOCATION> expressed awe
and respect for the power of the sea when he recalled the passage
around the cape.
   `It got pretty bad ... very unpleasant,'' <PERSON>Hazelton</PERSON> said in an
interview by radio last week. He said they spent six days and nights
sailing into the teeth of wind gusting to 60 knots, through seas
that raged from all directions.
</TEXT>
