streets in San Jose on Thursday night. The demonstrators expressed opposition
to United States' entry into war with Iraq.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SF-BAY-AREA; PROTEST; MIDEAST; WAR; IRAQ; US; MILITARY; ASSAULT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Golden Gate Bridge officials, responding to anti-war protests that shut down
the span earlier in the week, today were considering fines of up to $10,000
for people arrested while blocking the bridge.;    To keep the city's main
bridges open, authorities closed the Golden Gate Bridge to pedestrians early
Thursday and massed along the on-ramps to the San Francisco-Oakland Bay
Bridge, which protesters closed for periods on Tuesday and Wednesday.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BRIDGE OFFICIALS WEIGH PROTEST FINES
UP TO $10,000 CONSIDERED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULF
See also related stories on pages 1A-12A of this section.
Mercury News staff writer Jim Dickey and the Associated Press contributed to
this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "We are trying to devise some penalty other than a slap on the wrist for
disruption," said <ORGANIZATION>Golden Gate Bridge District</ORGANIZATION> board member <PERSON>Gary Giacomini</PERSON>.
"The bridge is a vital artery for many people no matter how noble the cause of
the demonstration.";    The proposal is "just another in the tactics of
intimidation and harassment to make us fearful of our right to demonstrate,"
said <PERSON>Riva Enteen</PERSON>, demonstrations coordinator for the <LOCATION>Bay Area</LOCATION> chapter of the
<ORGANIZATION>National Lawyers Guild</ORGANIZATION> that is providing free legal services to the
demonstrators.;    "They can try to raise the fine if they want, but there's
going to be a lot of fighting in the courts over these cases," she said.;   
Currently, a maximum fine of <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY> can be imposed on bridge trespassers. The
state Legislature would have to authorize the increased fine. The bridge board
will see the proposed changes <DATE>Jan. 25.</DATE>;    At dusk <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, stunned by news
of the Iraqi attack on <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>, somber and teary-eyed protesters gathered in
downtown <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> on the third straight day of anti-war demonstrations
that have filled this city with a deep sadness.;    Anger over <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
involvement in the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION> that had been expressed so stridently in
protests <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and earlier <DATE>Thursday</DATE> appeared dampened by grief and fear.; 
  "I'm very upset about it," said a weeping <PERSON>Debra Davis</PERSON>, 24, who said she has
relatives serving in the gulf. "I think this means that eventually it will
turn into a world war.";    Others expressed disbelief and deep frustration.; 
  "I can't believe it's happening," said <PERSON>Stephan Morgan</PERSON>, 24, who, unlike many
in the group, was dressed in a sports jacket and tie. "I don't know what the
American people can do to stop this. I feel very confused.";    Protesters
wound slowly through the city's downtown and neighborhood streets, sometimes
roaring for peace, sometimes chanting softly for an end to the war. There were
no violent incidents and participants seemed determined to keep the march
peaceful.;    Earlier in the day, a somewhat larger crowd of about 3,000
disrupted the city's financial district. By <TIME>late afternoon</TIME>, at least 1,000 had
been arrested.;    An overtaxed police force jumped on municipal buses in
desperate efforts to chase the demonstrators, who switched targets from the
Federal Building to oil companies to the <ORGANIZATION>Pacific Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION> and major
highways each time they were rousted from the pavement.;    Most of those
arrested <DATE>Thursday</DATE> were back on the streets within an hour, and at times
riot-clad police didn't move against groups blocking major intersections
because they had no place left in the city's <ORGANIZATION>Hall of Justice</ORGANIZATION> to process
demonstrators. So by afternoon, they began booking protesters at Pier 40.;   
All those arrested on misdemeanor charges were cited and released.;   
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s demonstrations, though loud and disruptive, nevertheless were
largely peaceful, unlike those <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, when police cars were burned
and military recruiting offices looted.;    Officers were working 12- to
21-hour shifts to keep up with the three days of rolling protests.;    "We're
chasing them from one end of town to the other," said Lt. <PERSON>Daniel Hallisy</PERSON> as he
watched helplessly at a midday protest of about 2,000 demonstrators outside
the <ORGANIZATION>Pacific Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION> on Pine Street. "We just don't know what they're
going to do.";    Hundreds of business people stood outside to watch. A plane
circled overhead, trailing a banner saying, "Go Desert Storm. Support our
troops.";    Although scuffles broke out between demonstrators and police, few
injuries were reported.;    As on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, the day of the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION>
deadline for <ORGANIZATION>Iraq</ORGANIZATION> to get out of <LOCATION>Kuwait</LOCATION>, protesters were out before dawn to
block all entrances to the city's Federal Building.;    Federal prosecutor
<PERSON>Mike Howard</PERSON> pleaded with demonstrators to let him get to his office. "I have a
major cocaine case I've got going," he said. "This dealer is killing our kids
on the street and I want to get in." Protesters standing six deep refused to
let him pass.;    In <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, about 200 people, including numerous high
school students, gathered at the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Building</ORGANIZATION> downtown in a peaceful
protest of the war, as groups have done there every day since <DATE>Monday</DATE>. On
<DATE>Thursday</DATE>, though, they had some competition: About 25 people in favor of the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military action staged a counterdemonstration across the street.  </TEXT>
