<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Lloyd Francis Jr. -- Mercury News; FREEWAY SNARL -- Charlotte
Swig of the mayor's office tells people to stand back from the Embarcadero
demolition site after several began grabbing chunks of the freeway.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  SAN-FRANCISCO; ROAD; END; EARTHQUAKE; DAMAGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The view from San Francisco became more spectacular Wednesday.;    The
Embarcadero Freeway, despised for three decades for shearing off San
Franciscans' vista of the bay, began crumbling to dust shortly after noon.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EMBARCADERO COMES TUMBLING DOWN
CHEERS GREET RAZING OF ROAD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Mayor Art Agnos stepped into the cab of a red-and-white hydraulic ram and
took the first whack at the 60-foot-high double-decker freeway, closed since
the <DATE>1989</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>Loma Prieta earthquake.</ORGANIZATION>;    For a funeral, albeit for a freeway, the
mourners certainly were in jovial spirits.;    Singers belted out favorites
ranging from "Shake, Rattle and Roll" to "If I Had a Hammer." Fireworks
lighted the gray sky and a fireboat sprayed plumes of water in the bay. Five
hundred onlookers chanted "Bring it down!";    The 1.7-mile elevated roadway
will be demolished in 90 days and replaced with a combination ground-level and
underground expressway.;    Wearing a hard hat, Agnos jumped from the
demolition vehicle as soon as the drill chipped off a piece from the freeway.
Flashing a thumbs-up sign to the crowd, Agnos pounced on the concrete scrap
and smashed it to the ground.;    The symbolism of Agnos' act was not lost on
the crowd or a generation of <LOCATION>San Franciscans</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Embarcadero Freeway</ORGANIZATION> had been
a thorny issue ever since it was erected in <DATE>1959.</DATE>;    Originally intended to
connect the Bay Bridge with the Golden Gate Bridge, the roadway was vehemently
opposed by environmentalists and neighborhood activists, who forced <ORGANIZATION>Caltrans</ORGANIZATION>
to stop construction before finishing the job.;    <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> became a city
with a permanently unfinished freeway that didn't go anywhere. Instead of
connecting to the Golden Gate Bridge, the freeway abruptly stopped near the
waterfront.;    Before construction crews were ordered to pack up, though, the
freeway went to <LOCATION>Chinatown</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>North Beach</LOCATION>, two popular tourist venues.;   
Merchants in those neighborhoods said the freeway, which carried 60,000
vehicles on an average weekday, was their lifeline. Throughout the <DATE>1970s</DATE> and
<DATE>'80s</DATE>, they effectively quashed any proposed legislation to tear down the
roadway, officially known as <LOCATION>Interstate 480.</LOCATION>;    Still, many politicians tried
to raze what everyone agreed was an eyesore. Former Mayor <PERSON>Dianne Feinstein</PERSON>
proposed demolishing it, but was unable to summon enough votes on the <ORGANIZATION>Board of
Supervisors</ORGANIZATION>. In <DATE>1986</DATE>, voters defeated a ballot measure to tear it down.;    In
<DATE>1987</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>American Institute of Architects</ORGANIZATION> held a competition to solicit ideas
on how to camouflage the clunky cul-de-sac. The winning design was a visionary
twin waterfall from the freeway's top and lower decks that would double as a
Yosemite-like nature shower and urban car wash.;    Since the <DATE>Oct. 17, 1989</DATE>
earthquake, the elevated freeway had been used as illegal site for roller
skaters, joggers, and late-night beer-drinking carousers who shared one of <LOCATION>San
Francisco</LOCATION> prettiest views.;    No one is saying that the demolition will be
painless. Tens of thousands of downtown-bound cars will have to be rerouted.
The freeway's concrete will be crushed on site, and its 60,000 cubic yards
will be enough to fill more than 5,000 dump trucks. More than 10,000 gallons
of reclaimed water will be sprayed at the site per day to control swirling
dust.;    Heavy rain dampened attendance <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, but not enthusiasm.;   
The city's famed Gay Men's Chorus sang "<LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>" a cappella. The <ORGANIZATION>Ethel
Merman Memorial Choir</ORGANIZATION>, a troupe of high-heeled and heavily rouged women and
men wearing hard hats, took center stage under the freeway. Lyrics included:; 
  "Shake, rattle and roll;    "Living on a fault line can sure takes its
toll.";    Uncharacteristic of most <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> events, there was no loyal
opposition present.;    "We come here not to praise the freeway, but to bury
it," said former <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> Supervisor <PERSON>Jack Morrison</PERSON> at the freeway
funeral.;    "It's not often in our civic life, we have an opportunity to
correct a 32-year-old mistake. In that way, the <LOCATION>Loma Prieta</LOCATION> earthquake was
kind to <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>," said Morrison.;    There were other options to tearing
down "the monster," as <PERSON>Allan Temko</PERSON>, the Pulitzer Prize-winning architecture
critic for the <LOCATION>San Francisco Chronicle</LOCATION>, has for years termed the freeway.;   
Repairing it would have been much less expensive, according to <ORGANIZATION>Caltrans</ORGANIZATION>.
Retrofitting the existing structure would have cost <MONEY>$69 million</MONEY>, as opposed to
tearing the Embarcadero down (<MONEY>$10 million</MONEY>) and building the new expressway
(<MONEY>$135 million</MONEY>).;    The federal government has allocated <MONEY>$59 million</MONEY>, with
state and other federal sources, along with sale of property along the
roadway, paying for the rest.  </TEXT>
