<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: 'The state should provide a bridge but perhaps not a Golden Gate
Bridge. '-- John Garamendi  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; GOVERNMENT; OFFICIAL; EARTHQUAKE; INSURANCE; PROGRAM  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The state's new earthquake insurance program is under-funded and should be
delayed six months past its July 1 start-up date to prevent insolvency,
Insurance Commissioner John Garamendi said.;    Garamendi urged a legislative
committee Wednesday to put off the July 1 start-up date for the program while
officials consider issues including increased premiums, higher deductibles and
reduced coverage for California homeowners.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NEW QUAKE INSURANCE PROGRAM SHOULD BE DELAYED,
GARAMENDI SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "The state," <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> said, "should provide a bridge but perhaps not a
Golden Gate Bridge.";    The state-run pool was created last year to be
exactly that -- a bridge policy to cover damage that is not covered by
commercial earthquake insurance policies, which typically have deductibles of
<MONEY>$15,000</MONEY> or more.;    As it was designed, the state pool would cover damage up
to <MONEY>$15,000</MONEY> with a <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY> deductible and an average annual premium of <MONEY>$36</MONEY> to be
added on to existing homeowners insurance policies.;    That would have been
enough coverage for most of the homes damaged -- but not entirely destroyed --
by the <LOCATION>Whittier</LOCATION> earthquake in <DATE>1987</DATE> and the <LOCATION>Loma Prieta</LOCATION> earthquake in <DATE>1989</DATE>,
officials said.;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON>, the state's first elected insurance
commissioner, said several serious problems with the state pool must still be
solved, especially a loophole that allows homeowners to withhold payments
without penalty.;    In addition, he said the preliminary studies show that
the premium level -- a sliding scale from <MONEY>$12</MONEY> to <MONEY>$60</MONEY> a year with an average
payment of <MONEY>$36</MONEY> -- would not raise enough money to pay all the claims from a
major quake.;    "In my judgment, the numbers don't work in the early years or
the later years," the Democratic insurance commissioner said after the
hearing.;    He said that it will take an average annual premium of <MONEY>$93</MONEY> to
provide <MONEY>$15,000</MONEY> in earthquake coverage for the state's approximately 6 million
homeowners.;    The average cost of homeowners insurance on a <MONEY>$250,000</MONEY> house
built in <DATE>1984</DATE> is currently <MONEY>$789</MONEY> a year, according to figures compiled by the
state <ORGANIZATION>Department of Insurance.</ORGANIZATION>;    <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> also said that the deductible
should be increased from <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY> to <PERCENT>5 percent</PERCENT> of a home's value. For a <MONEY>$250,000</MONEY>
home, for example, that would mean a deductible of <MONEY>$12,500</MONEY>. <PERSON>Garamendi</PERSON> also
called for limiting coverage to houses and excluding "cosmetics" such as
driveways, sidewalks and sheds.;    He asked that the start-up date for the
program be pushed back from <DATE>July 1</DATE> to <DATE>Jan. 1, 1992</DATE>, to allow further study on
how to scale back coverage and increase premiums to make the fund solvent.;   
Insurance industry officials testifying at the <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> insurance subcommittee
hearing agreed that the program should be delayed six months.;    "The
handwriting is on the wall," said <PERSON>Tim Hart</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Association of California
Insurance Companies</ORGANIZATION>. "The program can't be done, can't be made to work by <DATE>July
1</DATE>."  </TEXT>
